#2.3 Time series patterns

Patterns can be: Trend, seasonal and Cyclic.

ggseason

a10 %>%
  gg_season(Cost, labels = "both") + #note 
  labs(y = "$ (millions)",
       title = "Seasonal plot: Antidiabetic drug sales")

##vic_elec

#2.6 Scatterplots

vic_elec %>%
  filter(year(Time) == 2014) %>%
  autoplot(Demand) +

       title = "Half-hourly electricity demand: Victoria")

  filter(year(Time) == 2014) %>%
  autoplot(Temperature) +
  labs(
    y = "Degrees Celsius",
    title = "Half-hourly temperatures: Melbourne, Australia"
  )

##Correlation Plot

vic_elec %>%
  filter(year(Time) == 2014) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Temperature, y = Demand)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Temperature (degrees Celsius)",
       y = "Electricity demand (GW)")

##Scatterplot Matrices

visitors <- tourism %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarise(Trips = sum(Trips))
visitors %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Quarter, y = Trips)) +
  geom_line() +
  facet_grid(vars(State), scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title = "Australian domestic tourism",
       y= "Overnight trips ('000)")

##Relationships

visitors %>%
  pivot_wider(values_from=Trips, names_from=State) %>%
  GGally::ggpairs(columns = 2:9)

#2.7 Lag plots

recent_production <- aus_production %>%
  filter(year(Quarter) >= 2000)
recent_production %>%
  gg_lag(Beer, geom = "point") +
  labs(x = "lag(Beer, k)")

#2.8 Autocorrelation

ACF is a function to calculate the correlation between lagged values of a time series.

recent_production %>% ACF(Beer, lag_max = 9)
## # A tsibble: 9 x 2 [1Q]
##     lag      acf
##   <lag>    <dbl>
## 1    1Q -0.0530 
## 2    2Q -0.758  
## 3    3Q -0.0262 
## 4    4Q  0.802  
## 5    5Q -0.0775 
## 6    6Q -0.657  
## 7    7Q  0.00119
## 8    8Q  0.707  
## 9    9Q -0.0888
recent_production %>%
  ACF(Beer) %>%
  autoplot() + labs(title="Australian beer production")

#2.9 White noise

This looks like a residual plot. Those are the NO AUTOCORRELATION.

set.seed(30)
y <- tsibble(sample = 1:50, wn = rnorm(50), index = sample) #create a new data set with random numbers, index is also being determined.
y %>% autoplot(wn) + labs(title = "White noise", y = "")

y %>%
  ACF(wn) %>%
  autoplot() + labs(title = "White noise")
